entry.title: Add a ForceHeuristicMemorySaver feature
entry.content:
This feature will enable or disable the HeuristicMemorySaverPolicy

based on the existing HeuristicmemorySaver feature, regardless of the

state of the HighEfficiencyModeState pref. The existing

HeuristicMemorySaver feature can still be used without this to set

parameters for the policy and to enable it for users who have turned

on HighEfficiencyMode. ForceHeuristicMemorySaver is ignored if the pref

is managed.



To experiment with this, experiment groups should enable

ForceHeuristicMemorySaver and HeuristicMemorySaver (with various

params), and the control group should enable ForceHeuristicMemorySaver

but disable HeuristicMemorySaver.



Also includes various test cleanups.



R=charlesmeng

entry.title: Resolves cursor flickering issue for screensharing
entry.content:
This change fixes a widely spread issue where the cursor could

flicker or leave a trail when sharing the screen. It mainly affected

Windows clients which used the DXGI capture API.



Bisecting was performed in [1] and the culprit was identified as [2].

It was however not able to simply revert [2] since other features

have been added since it first landed.



A detailed description of what the root case was and what this CL

fixes can be found in [3].



This CL restores the working version while maintaining the new parts

which has been added with one expectation: support of the

RequestRefreshFrame (RRF) API.



Before this change, the DCD kept a reference to the last captured

frame as was always willing to deliver a copy of it when a client

asked for it via RRF. This is no longer the case since the mentioned

ownership was part of the issue we tried to fix here, and being able

to always deliver a copy of the latest captured frame is not

necessarily what the RRF contract stipulates.



In this new version, RRF is still supported but it works a bit

differently. I've tried to make it as simple as possible since it

is not clearly specified if/when a client needs it.



A summary of the new RRF scheme is given below:



* RRF is called before default capture has started => no-op.

* RRF is called after default capture has stopped => no-op.

* RRF is called while default capture is running results in that a

refresh timer starts with a timeout of 2 x (default capture time)

and a max of 1 second. E.g. ~67ms for 30 fps. The timer is stopped

if a default capture event happens before it triggers and if a new

RRF attempt takes place while one is already active, the new is

ignored. Once the RRF timer triggers, and if no capture event is

active, a new capture call will take place and the client will get

a new frame.



As a result, using the RRF API will rarely trigger an extra call

to CaptureFrame as long as the default capture stream is active and

running as normal. I.e., it is no longer possible to "force" a new

captured frame; instead one will be provided in a reasonable time-

frame but only if the default flow is not working as intended. And,

if that is the case, a RRF attempt will most likely also fail.

In summary, there is no longer a guarantee that a RRF attempt will

trigger a new capture event.



Example of a case where two early back-to-back calls from a client

triggers one RRF: https://paste.googleplex.com/6546502678740992.

Note that, in this example the RRF is able to be triggered since it

is requested directly from the start and then comes after the first

default captured frame and this takes an extra long time due to extra

initializations. It means that the RRF latency is low in comparison

with the next calculated default timer delay and is then triggered.

One could argue that we should instead try to reduce the latency of

the second frame since we *know* that the first is always extra

complex. If we did so, the RRF in this example would not be triggered.



I have also disabled one unittest related to RRF since I don't want to

delay landing a fix for the flickering issue. My plan was to sort out

the exact expectations of how RRF should work but I wanted to avoid

ending up in designing complex unittests for some very unique cases

that are hard to reproduce in real life.

[2] https://chromium.googlesource.com/chromium/src/+/6fcde169c4b1d828128ebf54fcf158d8a7f9ba45

[3] https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1421656#c99

entry.title: Remove deprecated content::ExecuteScript function
entry.content:
content::ExecJs is mostly a drop-in replacement for

content::ExecuteScript. Differences are:

* ExecJs waits for promise resolution by default - so callers may need

to supply EXECUTE_SCRIPT_NO_RESOLVE_PROMISES to retain current

behavior.

* ExecJs has stricter variable scoping rules. Scripts that define

variables which need to be used from another script execution must

use `var`, instead of `const` or `let`. (`const` and `let` can and

should be for variables that don't need to escape the current script

execution.)

* ExecJs's return value is [[nodiscard]]. Callers can no longer

implicitly ignore the success/failure of script execution.

entry.title: [sync] Defer sync startup even if SESSIONS isn't preferred
entry.content:
Before this CL, deferred startup was only performed if SESSIONS was

preferred (the fallback being immediate startup). Our team doesn't know

any good reasons for this fact; the logic was introduced in

https://codereview.chromium.org/181093002, but no clear rationale is documented in crbug.com/80194. Furthermore, it means changes to

GetPreferredTypes() might have subtle performance impacts. Let's drop

the check.



Due to past migrations, there is a significant mobile population with

sync-the-feature on but "all" data types disabled, including SESSIONS.

It will be the main affected group affected by this CL. They will

entry.title: [iOS] Fix Find Navigator resigning first responder when tab grid closes
entry.content:
When Native Find in Page (with the iOS 16 Find panel) is triggered,

the Find navigator view becomes first responder in a separate window,

i.e. not the key window. This is a problem because when the tab switcher

is dismissed, the tab grid coordinator will only look for a first

responder in the key window. Since it cannot find one, it will set the

BVC's view as first responder instead and the Find navigator will be

dismissed.



This CL changes how the tab grid coordinator decides on a new first

responder once it is done dismissing the tab switcher and presenting a

tab view controller on top of it. Specifically, instead of setting the

current BVC as first responder if no first responder has been found in

any key window in any connected scene, we now seek a first responder in

any of the windows of the current BVC's view's windowScene.



As a result, if the Find navigator is the first responder in a separate

window, instead of ignoring it and setting the BVC as first responder,

the Find navigator will remain first responder.



Fixed: 1442502

> [wayland] Cancel dnd when drag target or dragged window destroyed

entry.title: [Files]: Hide trash files from search results.
entry.content:
Adds an excluded_paths parameter to SearchByPattern function. This

parameter allows us to specify paths which are used to reject a matched

file, if any of the excudeld paths is a parent to the found file path.

In searchFiles function we populate this parameter with known locations

of Trash folders. Adjusts the tests to the new specs.
